<div class="syndicationHeadline"><div class='ftbf-syndicationIndicator' data-uuid='5a5325d6-a872-11e4-bd17-00144feab7de'><a href='http://ftsyndication.com/redirect.php?uuid=5a5325d6-a872-11e4-bd17-00144feab7de&title=How%20political%20revolutions%20shaped%20Warsaw&rsquo;s%20postwar%20architecture&action=article' target='_blank'>Download</a></div><h1>How political revolutions shaped Warsaw&rsquo;s postwar architecture</h1></div>
<p class="byline ">
<span>Martin Sandbu</span></p>
</div>
<script>FT.$doc.trigger("pgObjStop", {key: "8"});</script>
<script>FT.$doc.trigger("pgObjStart", {key: "9", keyType: "el"});</script>
<input type="hidden" name="headline" id="headline" value="How political revolutions shaped Warsaw’s postwar architecture" />
<div class="fullstory fullstoryBody specialArticle" data-comp-name="fullstory" data-comp-view="fullstory" data-comp-index="1" data-timer-key="9">
<div class="standfirst">
A look at how the Polish capital has sought to reinvent itself through its buildings over the past 70 years
</div>
<div id="storyContent"><div class="slideshow slideshow-standard carousel" data-feature-group="f3804312-acc6-11e4-beeb-00144feab7de" data-feature-type="slideshow"><ul class="carousel-collection"><li class="carousel-item"><img src="http://im.ft-static.com/content/images/8b729749-b2a1-4cef-a77a-12af381a3082.img" alt="" width="600" height="338" /><div class="slide-overlay">Muranów, site of Warsaw Ghetto, at the end of the war<div class="slide-imageSource"><span class="credit manualSource">©SovFoto/Getty Images</span></div></div></li><li class="carousel-item"><noscript data-src="http://im.ft-static.com/content/images/0653b942-ee9b-43b5-b85f-bfe82ec438bf.img" data-alt="" data-width="600" data-height="338"><img src="http://im.ft-static.com/content/images/0653b942-ee9b-43b5-b85f-bfe82ec438bf.img" alt="" width="600" height="338" /></noscript><div class="slide-overlay">Muranów in the late 1950s after it was rebuilt<div class="slide-imageSource"><span class="credit manualSource">©SovFoto/Getty Images.jpg</span></div></div></li><li class="carousel-item"><noscript data-src="http://im.ft-static.com/content/images/58afab16-5117-4159-a952-3c2c28e2ba1c.img" data-alt="" data-width="600" data-height="338"><img src="http://im.ft-static.com/content/images/58afab16-5117-4159-a952-3c2c28e2ba1c.img" alt="" width="600" height="338" /></noscript><div class="slide-overlay">Old Town Market Place, built in the 1950s, is an example of historicist reconstruction<div class="slide-imageSource"><span class="credit manualSource">©Jorg Greuel</span></div></div></li><li class="carousel-item"><noscript data-src="http://im.ft-static.com/content/images/b2d767cc-dcb9-425b-927a-184bdfeb50c7.img" data-alt="" data-width="600" data-height="338"><img src="http://im.ft-static.com/content/images/b2d767cc-dcb9-425b-927a-184bdfeb50c7.img" alt="" width="600" height="338" /></noscript><div class="slide-overlay">Youths marching outside the socialist realist MDM residential complex in 1952<div class="slide-imageSource"